es of wine; grape growing, wine production, and wine distribution activities; wine firms and consumers; grape and wine markets; and wine globalization. Thornton employs economic principles to explain how grape growers, wine producers, distributors, retailers, and consumers interact and influence the wine market. The volume includes a summary of findings and presents insights from the growing body of studies related to wine economics. Economic concepts, supplemented by numerous examples and anecdotes, are used to gain insight into wine firm behavior and the importance of contractual arrangements in the industry. Thornton also provides a detailed analysis of wine consumer behavior and what studies reveal about the factors that dictate wine-buying decisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWine and wine makingzUnited States. 0aWine industryzUnited States. 0aWinexMarketing. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aalcoholic.  aamerican culture.  abeverages.  abusiness.  abuying decisions.  acapitalism.  aconsumers.  acooking.  aeconomic circumstances.  aeconomic concepts.  aeconomic principles.  aeconomics.  aengaging.  afood and wine.  agrape growing.  agrape markets.  agrape.  ahospitality.  alarge market.  aretailers.  aus wine industry.  awine distribution.  awine economics.  awine firms.  awine globalization.  awine markets.  awine production.  awine professionals.  awine tourism.  awine trade.  awine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027649940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095701540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957015423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.